The 2001 economic feasibility study was based on the assumption that the section that crosses the border and the section that passes through the Bohemian Central Mountains would go under traffic at the same time.
At the time of the test it was obvious that the section through the Bohemian Central Mountains will not be opened on the original date.
This reduces the above EIRR values.
The costs of both sections amounted to €897 million excluding VAT as of 31 December 2005, which was 27.4% higher than in the 2001 economic perspective.
In addition, there is a risk that Section 0805 will have a different, more burdensome course of action, which would affect the economic viability of the project.
The economic analysis showed that the construction of both motorway sections with a daily traffic volume of at least 18 000 vehicles per day in 2010 is economically justified. The forecast for 2008 had predicted 22 940 vehicles per day.
However, a study of diversion routes as an alternative to the missing section through the Bohemian Mid-Mountain is based on a traffic volume of 12 600 to 13 750 vehicles per day in 2007. The project is then below the economic limit.
Increased traffic on the routes to replace the missing section through the Czech Central Mountains is likely to result in congestion and thus increased external costs, which were not taken into account in the original economic analysis.
The mentioned reduction in revenue and increase in costs means that the already low EIRR for the construction of the borderline section of the D 8 will not be achieved.
The construction of the bordering section of the D 8 is therefore uneconomic.
The cost of the construction of the A 17 also increased, as did the construction of the two above-mentioned sections of the D 8.
In the context of the general economic assessment for the Federal Transport Plan 1992, the Federal Ministry responsible for Transport assumed investment costs of approx. €320 million.
Thus it determined a benefit / cost ratio of 4.6.
In the meantime, the costs have increased to around €670 million and the benefit / cost ratio has been reduced by more than half.
The BRH independently of the parallel tests with the NKÚ in the years 2003 to 2005 had examined the economic viability of the planning and construction of the motorway A 17.
It found that the authorisation authority requested a non-necessary landscape tunnel for the third section of the A17.
In the course of the examination, the BRH succeeded in convincing the Federal Ministry and the Road Administration of the superfluousness of the landscape tunnel.
This avoided €10 million in construction costs and €150 000 in annual operating costs.
When examining the first section of A 17, the BRH found that the construction project was inadequately prepared.
The following example illustrates this:
During the planning phase, the road building administration refrained from recording the condition of the rock on the surface of the Dölzschener Wall, as it was difficult to access it.
Only when the tunnel drive reached the wall did it catch up.
It turned out that the rock had weathered more strongly than was assumed at the time of the tender.
Extensive measures such as anchorages, injections and stone impact protection nets for around €3.3 million became necessary.
The road construction administration was responsible not only for the costs of additional services that were already required, such as securing the Dölzschener Wall, but also for those that would not have been necessary if the construction had been properly prepared.
These include expenditure due to disrupted construction processes (€3.2 million), additional training of the sales team (€0.5 million) and increased wages and material prices due to the extension of the construction time (€7 million).
This additional expenditure of around €10.7 million does not represent any lasting added value.
The BRH took these and other measures as an opportunity to call on the Federal Ministry to better exercise its responsibility for the technical supervision of major road construction measures.
In this context, it should insist that the road authorities introduce quality assurance systems.
Benefits of cooperation for BRH and NKÚ The cooperation met the expectations of both Court of Auditors.
The BRH received information on the planning, procurement and implementation of the construction of the border bridge.
Both Court of Auditors have developed a database of bridge and tunnel prices which will be useful in future audits.
The NKÚ found that the most important structural parameters for bridges, tunnels and carriageways of the D 8 did not differ from those of the A 17.
The auditors of both Court of Auditors involved in the cooperation gained valuable experience which will be useful in future audits.
